text: You know..I'd actually be way more excited for this if they didn't keep intentionally placing Jennifer Lawrence/Mystique at the front of every team shot and then having her make the big leader speech that should really be coming from Cyclops, a character that really deserves some focus by now. He is the ACTUAL leader of the X-MEN after all. It also bugs me that they keep coming up with contrivances to have Mystique look human. Yes fine, Jen's a big star now and we can't use Jackman for much longer so you want to emphasis that she's in this film, I get that, but it goes against the whole point of Mystique as a character. She's kinda being a bit of a hypocrite telling everyone not to be ashamed of their abilities if she keeps turning into her human-looking self every time she steps outside. I'm hopeful for this film, and I like Bryan Singer's respect for the source material's subtext more than most, regardless of the kinda bland blue/silvery look he tends to go for in these films but the stuff with Cyclops, Jean and Nightcrawler looks WAY more interesting than baby-faced Mystique and I'm fearful we might not get it...

text: I know I'm probably not the first person to ask this, but what would have happened to Apocalypse in the main timeline? I know the go-to answer would be "Oh, the sentinels took care of him", but this movie's events are set just a few years after the DoFP past events, the sentinels that would've in theory killed Apocalypse would've been very similar to the ones from the DoFP past. I can't honestly believe that those sentinels, which had trouble taking care of a handful of mutants that weren't prepared to fight sentinels, could handle, let alone defeat, the power of a god and his empowered followers. Don't get me wrong, I'm still excited for the movie, but to me that's just a plot hole too big to ignore.

text: I think the X-men don't have enough substance, like, at all. Why does everyone asks "where's Wolverine?" you ask? Well, he completes the team in a certain way.  But this version of the X-men kinda looks like, well, weak (not that the other ones were strong)?!! especially Bryan Singers directing skills are not good enough for the scale of an Apocalypse, every shot feels so alone and the World where the Movie plays just feels empty. Look at Man of Steel, B vs S, Lord of the rings, the World seems alive, consequences are possible, for example now in the new Civil War trailer, we see how the actions of the first Avengers movie had an effect on humanity, but this ? It feels empty, dry and kinda hipsterish I guess, "let's get young actors from popular shows" was the Idea behind the casting, it feels lazy and the script as little as we know, was just, meh. I know, no one should judge a book by its cover but this is just the same with Deadpool, everything worth mentioning already happened. from an early perspective: 6.0/10  Trailers should get us excited, while not telling us exactly what happens (like the Suicide Squad trailers) this looks at best mediocre.

text: So far, I have been less than impressed with these two trailers, and personally, I've never been too indulged with the prequel X-MEN films other than DoFP, which involved both incarnations of each character's. I also remember that Fox is responsible for the bomb that is Fantastic Four, but then I remember that it's also responsible for the glory that is Deadpool. I'm very torn on this film. Remembering how good DoFP really puts a smile on my face, but then again, it was mainly Wolverine who brought the whole movie together. Without him, there wouldn't have even been a plot to begin with! I don't know. I'm not very hyped for this film, as the two ginormous superhero showdowns will premiere before this, but I'm not completely shutting it off. It's a "wait and see" for me.

Also, making mystique such a central character on account of it being played by Jennifer Lawrence doesn't sit well with me. The whole xmen universe, for me, revolved on the opposing ideologies of Xavier and magneto which was later developed into apocalypse's and mr sinister' belief system. Mystique is maybe at the most a knight on the chessboard. In summary, I got mixed feelings about this movie as I did with first class, wolverine origins and x3. text: Terrible rendition of Apocalypse and his Horsemen. I have always enjoyed Marvel over DC in comics, but in movies DC gets it right more often.The Marvel movies just look and feel cheesy and cheap. The backgrounds(sets) are too bright and generic and just don't feel immerseful. DC is dark and gritty. A tone that should be set for what story is suppose to be going on.The backgrounds compliment the characters and the mood. Apoc looks like a fool in this. Just like Thanos (which their first showing of him actually looked good), they made him look awful. Thanos' head is too big for his body and looks like a gourd. In comics he was built like the Hulk. Both Apoc and Thanos are menacing, intimidating characters just on looks alone. Evil, dark and twisted.  The movies just need to stop. You can't get something right that was mainly geared to market kids merchandise. Yes I know comics were mostly too. It just would have been nice to see an adult spin be given to them.The idea in the beginning was for the directors to give them that much wanted approach. That went by the wayside fast for dollar signs. I know they took a different approach with Deadpool. But one right doesn't undo all the wrong.

text: it should be noted that even though this movie can't be as bad as X-3....that still shouldn't auto-generate blind fandom. It looks good on the premise....but: certain characters (mytique) taking the lead;  other characters (Cyclops) not being what they are in the old school animated series we grew up with - a badass leader; Proper romance that doesnt take over the movie like Cyclops-Jean (where they should have happy endings) and Rogue (sexy  rogue please, not a kiddy) - Gambit romance that's sad but equally as satisfying to see them make it work;  are the kinds of details that gave animated series its heart. It wasnt the focus - that was always they relationships between them, but it was pleasant complications that added depth to the characters.  after movies like deadpool and civil war, im expecting this one to be average from what ive seen thus far - but its hard to get excited when the LEGIT source material is being adapted so.....recklessly

The concept is ridiculous until I realized they did the same thing in Last Stand when Wolverine and Storm lead the X-youngins against Magneto, Juggernaut and Dark Phoenix. But you can make a case for Wolverine being able to kill Dark Phoenix. Who is going to get within a mile of Apocalypse? text: So Apocalypse has a British accent?  So what? Since he being touted as a near God being able to speak in new languages or accents would require little effort. Just think how many movies where the characters are now supposedly speaking in the "Genuine Native Language" of a place or a time. They are actually speaking a version or using words that the original societies never ever used. True ancient people would not recognise the supposed "True Native Language" being used in the movies. Egypt is called Egypt by everyone yet it is not the original native name for that country. Same as Greece and many more. So don't worry about accent or language and don't be a nerd. Just enjoy the movie its make pretend after all!!

text: Honestly I don't understand some of these comments. The original trilogy people were up in arms how they didn't stick to the comics. Now people are up in arms over how the CGI looks off, or how it doesn't feel like a comic book movie, wolverines not in it, or that it's a bad plot. Let me educate the masses, first this is the origin of the xmen and wolverine was not an original member and two Hugh Jackman is almost 50 years old he can't play him forever. Three you guys are complaining about the CGI but how exactly to you expect to have an xmen movie with no CGI or Green screen? Can we look at the avengers movies and GOTG a lot the villains were CGI and backgrounds too and so was the Hulk and Scarlet Witches powers(which definitely looked worse than Psylockes in terms of cgi) so if the Avengers is mostly CGI and green screen how is it you can complain out the xmen, people like to hate. Four we have costumes that ARE from the comics, we have characters that look JUST like there comic book characters (nightcrawler, storm, angel, psylocke) how is it that it doesn't look like a comic book movie. The people who made the film changed Apocalypses voice over outraged fans in the comics yet people are still complaining about it. And the ones complaining about the plot go read the comics the plot has been established long before it was a movie, go watch the cartoon show too while your at it or play xmen legends 2. Point is i'm saying instead of criticizing this trailer and film for things you would not criticize about other marvel movies and being to knit picky and particular ( because I swear someone will leave a comment like I don't like Charles is breathing in one shot ) can we enjoy and show excitement for the film, instead of taking time out of your life to write how you wont like it.

text: People are too busy complaining about mystique that they're not looking at the whole picture.  Which isn't shocking because that's all people do when it comes to these movies.   This is the ending to a story involving 4 people: Hank accepting himself, Raven finding out who she is (doesn't want to turn into Charles nor Eric), Charles accepting his role and his limitations,  and Eric coming to terms with his pain caused by others.     Please stop whining for a second and see what they're doing here.   Raven isn't hero nor villain.  Charles nor Eric.  She steps up when she needs to but is always fighting for her fellow mutants.  And this is the time that she stops taking orders from Charles and Eric and becomes a leader herself. She and beast become leaders because Charles is incapacitated  (again lol) and Eric has joined apocalypse  They're the only two with any experience. I know many wat cyclops to lead but he said in the gray trailer that they barely know how to control their powers.   Pay attention.  These plots have been building for 3 movies. Before anyone got "too famous".Ôªø

text: I would advise you to watch/re-watch 'The Mummy' (the 1999 version); 'Watchmen'; and 'The Avengers'. The same theme, content, archetypes, and messages are being conveyed through various franchises/storylines. Ultimately, the aim is to influence the masses psychologically through repetition. What are complaining about as far as staying close to the comic book or TV series is concerned is actually the filmmakers' intentional attempt to influence you with deliberate images, sounds, and scripted events. So if you are upset about something not being faithful to the comic/TV show, realize that the changes are purposeful and the ulterior motives behind it serve what the filmmakers intend on influencing in your psyche.

Jean Grey... and Storm.¬†¬† Check.¬†¬† All make sense and seems to adhere to the "logic" established in the original trilogy of films.¬†¬†¬† BUT my son and I are scratching our heads: How are we to reconcile the presence of a "young" Nightcrawler?....¬† And - even more challenging - how do we account for a "young" Angel?¬†¬† (Both were "introduced" to the Xmen in X-2 and X-3 respectively).¬†¬†¬† Are we guilty of seeking logic where none can be found?

text: The principal actor in this, apocalypse has to be the most terrible standout in this. His costume does him no justice for whom he is supposed to be. Where they tried to make him look the most indestructible, he looks the most childish. Almost as if he is just a kid saying look I have all these mutant powers I can make these grown up xmen do my bidding Nah, nah, nah. The dialogue is there to make apocalypse what the real apocalypse is supposed to be but man; even Xmen TAS apocalypse has a better rendering than this one. Less is always more. ¬† If Bryan Singer wanted to go all out with a heinous costume of what the harbinger of total destruction should look like he should have humbly called James Cameron and asked him to come on board and create a live action apocalypse for xmen fans. Bummer, there can only be one director. But of course this movie is for the broad run of the mill audience, so no pushing the budget for sanctity of comic lore sake! Course bringing James Cameron on board would probably put the release date back 3 more years to get the whole movie right as he would have unwittingly taken over prodction and letting Bryan sit as his side. I can hear him now "Okay now Bryan! This is the end of the master class. Do you think I can let you sit in the big chair again and not !@#$% up what I just put together". If Mr Cameron were directing this movie, I can only imagine what he would have in store for us with his renditions of Mystique, Storm, Night crawler, and of course Apocalypse. Less is more, we would see tiny characteristics in each xmen from the alien franchise in each their own way. The audience would never even notice unless they were alien fans. That's how good he would do it! Just my opinion!

text: Batman vs. Superman < X-Men: Apocalypse < Suicide Squad < Deadpool < Civil War X-Man: Apocalypse, in comparison to First Class and Days of Future Past, was extremely poor. Mischaracterization (making Mystique the hero), lazy writing (Magneto, once again, becoming the villain rather than the anti-hero he is in the comics/Age of Apocalypse storyline), lack of continuity (Quicksilver having Charles' business card even though Charles took it back, Logan ending up in Weapon X even though Raven saved him in DOFP), and excessive CGI really affected the quality of the film.  First Class and Days of Future Past, I feel, perfectly explored the emotional and philosophical depth the comics have. Peace vs. War, Oppressed vs. Privileged, Athleticism vs. Intelligence, Conformity vs. Pride -- all of these themes, which reflect the current society we endure, were brilliantly explored in the previous films. With Apocalypse, they ditched those themes and replaced them with star power and lazy writing.  The other films, while mostly disappointing and/or underwhelming, really captured the feel of the comics. The characters were properly written (although some background stories were FAR too rushed *cough* SS *cough*), the action sequences were (mostly) tame yet engaging, and the overall vibe made the other films feel great. They captured the spirit of the respective comics, and the universes they live in.

text: X-Men: Apocalypse is another example that good trailers doesn't necessarily mean a good movie. This is one of the most boring movies of the year. Apocalypse is a one dimensional villain that makes most MCU villains look good. Archangel, Pyslocke and Storm are wasted more than Hawkeye was in Avengers. The Wolverine cameo is so needless and is only there cause, you know, Wolverine. The CGI at time was good but for the most part it was really bad for the budget the film had. And the directing, it felt like Bryan Signer really wanted to make a Mortal Kombat movie, with the shots he had. Should have put in a "DOUBLE POINTS" voiceover. I've never been a huge lover of the X-Men films but this was just bad. Not as bad as X-Men Origins: Wolverine. Just bad.
